  <section class="mx-5 py-4">
    <h1>Why I Don&apos;t Change My Clocks When Daylight Saving Time Ends Every
      Year üïñ</h1>
    <p>{{!
      }}When the US west coast switches clocks in the fall, I opt out
      and stay on the same time zone and schedule as I had in the summer. This
      means in the winter, my schedule is one hour earlier than everyone
      else&apos;s.{{!
    }}</p>
    <ul>
      <li>PDT: Pacific Daylight Time, used in the summer on the west coast</li>
      <li>PST: Pacific &quot;Standard&quot; Time, used in the winter on the west
        coast</li>
    </ul>
    <h2>Why?</h2>
    <p>{{!
      }}I grew up in an area where there were no clock changes during
      the year. It doesn&apos;t make much sense to me to gain or lose one hour
      of sleep on arbitrary days in the middle of the year. When I followed the
      clock changes in the past, I also noticed certain disruptions in my
      circadian rhythm like when I would get hungry or tired. I prefer to keep
      my habits consistent throughout the year, aligned with when I see
      daylight.{{!
    }}</p>
    <p>{{!
      }}Additionally (and this is a big one), the earliest sunset in
      Seattle during the entire year is 16:17 PST, when it is equally 17:17 PDT.
      Why should we change clocks to make the sun appear to set earlier in the
      winter, when we actually need more daylight in the day?{{!
    }}</p>
    <h2>How does it work?</h2>
    <p>{{!
      }}I still go to things when they physically happen, but my
      clocks and watches are just one hour ahead at any physical point in time.
      It&apos;s as if I&apos;m living in a time zone where it is Pacific
      Daylight Time year-round, and Pacific Standard Time is not observed.
      Outside of my home, it is simply a different time zone, the same way
      someone can live near a town across a national/state line where it is a
      different time zone.{{!
    }}</p>
    <p>{{!
      }}Most of Arizona observes this time zone (Mountain Standard
      Time), where clocks do not switch throughout the year &mdash; PDT and MST
      are equivalent in the summer, but not the winter. I keep my devices and
      clocks in MST year-round, and any digital calendar tools will handle
      tougher time differences.{{!
    }}</p>
    <p>{{!
      }}In the winter, I mentally subtract an hour when making plans
      with others, and sometimes specify &quot;PST&quot; to clarify.{{!
    }}</p>
    <h2>Doesn&apos;t it get confusing?</h2>
    <p>{{!
      }}No, what&apos;s confusing is changing your clocks twice a
      year.
      {{!
    }}</p>
    <h2>Do you see any unintentional benefits in the winter?</h2>
    <p>{{!
      }}I am not a morning person, so an added benefit from my
      perspective is that businesses and restaurants magically close an hour
      later than their posted time. Instead of getting an extra hour once in the
      fall, I get an extra hour every day üòÅ.{{!
    }}</p>
    <p>{{!
      }}There is also now just a 2 hour time difference from the east
      coast.{{!
    }}</p>
    <h2>But not everyone has a flexible schedule.</h2>
    <p>{{!
      }}I do admit I have a relatively flexible schedule compared to
      people working in jobs requiring fixed hours. However, in the winter, I
      still tend to adapt to the rest of Seattle&apos;s schedule; for example at
      work, I won&apos;t decline a late meeting because it is later for me than
      for others, and my lunchtime is an hour later so I can eat with my
      coworkers. What I get out of staying on PDT is being more mindful of
      shorter days, sunrise and sunset times, and making myself start and end my
      day earlier to take advantage of the daylight. This is just something that
      works for me.{{!
    }}</p>
